Name: South Africa 10-Year Bond Yield (with GFD Extension)
Periodicity:
Monthly From Dec 1860 To Oct 1999
Weekly From Oct 1999 To Sep 2000
Daily From Oct 2000 To Jul 2025
Metadata:
Sources: The Economist (1860-1926), League of Nations, Statistical Yearbook, Geneva: League of Nations (1927-45), Reserve Bank of South Africa, Quarterly Bulletin (1946-71)
Notes: Cape Colony bonds are used through October 1913 when Union of South Africa bonds were floated on the London Stock Market. The Cape of Good Hope 6% Debentures of 1861 Redeemable 1880-1890 (BGCGH680-LO) are used between November 1860 and December 1864, the Cape of Good Hope 5% Bonds of 1865 (BGCGH565-LO) are used between January 1865 and April 1873, the Cape of Good Hope 4.50% Bonds of 1873-1878 (BGCGH45738-LO) are used between May 1873 and August 1881, the Cape of Good Hope 4% Bonds of 1881 (BGCGH481-LO) are used between September 1881 and December 1913. South African Union bonds are used beginning in 1914 with the South Africa 4% Consolidated Stock of 1913 (Redeemable 1943-1963) (BGZAF4S-LO) is used between January 1914 and December 1940, and the South Africa 5% Inscribed Bonds of 1925, 1926,1927 and 1930 (Redeemable 1945-1975) (BGZAF545-LO) is used between January 1941 and December 1942. Beginning in July 1941, South African quotations are used. The 3% obligations of 1951-56 begin in July 1941, and the 3% obligations of 1960-70 begin in 1944. The 4 1/4% bonds of 1954, maturing in 1974 are used from 1956 until 1971. 10-year benchmark bonds are used from 1972 to date.
